CROSS-VALIDATION AND TUNING MODEL SELECTION

Separation into training and testing sets
taxi_sample <- sample.int(n = nrow(taxi), size=500000, replace = F)
train_x <- taxi[taxi_sample, ]
train_y <- train_x$tip_amount
test_x  <- taxi[-taxi_sample, ] %>% sample_n(200000)
test_y <- test_x$tip_amount
mf<-model.frame(tip_amount~.+dow:hours, data=train_x)
#Model matrix with all relavent variables and interactions betweem all.
train_X<-model.matrix(tip_amount~.+dow:hours, mf)[,-1]
AIC calculations: lambda tuning
c("nvmax" = ncol(train_X))
## nvmax 
##    14
allyhat<-function(xtrain, ytrain, xtest,lambdas,nvmax=14){
  n<-nrow(xtrain)
  yhat<-matrix(nrow=nrow(xtest),ncol=length(lambdas))
  search<-regsubsets(xtrain,ytrain, nvmax=nvmax, method="back")
  summ<-summary(search)
  for(i in 1:length(lambdas)){
    penMSE<- n*log(summ$rss)+lambdas[i]*(1:nvmax)
    best<-which.min(penMSE)  #lowest AIC
    betahat<-coef(search, best) #coefficients
    xinmodel<-cbind(1,xtest)[,summ$which[best,]] #predictors in that model
    yhat[,i]<-xinmodel%*%betahat
  }
  yhat
}

n<-nrow(train_X)
folds<-sample(rep(1:10,length.out=n))
lambdas<-c(2,4,6,8,10,12)
fitted<-matrix(nrow=n,ncol=length(lambdas))
for(k in 1:10){
  train<- (1:n)[folds!=k]
  test<-(1:n)[folds==k]
  fitted[test,]<-allyhat(train_X[train,],train_y[train],train_X[test,],lambdas)  
}
colMeans((train_y-fitted)^2)
## [1] 1.837385 1.837364 1.837364 1.837388 1.837435 1.837490

MSPE for all different lambda’s are the same, so we cannot tune lambda values. Instead we will try it with parameters.

Tuning the number of variables - “p”
set.seed(520737112)
#Training data used in regsubsets.
#finding best 51 variable model.
search = regsubsets(train_X, train_y, nvmax =14, method = "backward")

#Test data used for MSPE.
mf1<-model.frame(tip_amount~.+dow:hours, data=test_x)
test_X<-model.matrix(tip_amount~.+dow:hours ,mf1)[,-1]

MSPE = numeric(14)
for (p in 1:14){    
  betahat<-coef(search, p)
  xinmodel<-cbind(1,test_X)[,summary(search)$which[p,]]
  yhat1<-xinmodel%*%betahat    
  MSPE[p]<-mean( (test_y-yhat1)^2)
  }

min_mspe <- which.min(MSPE)
c("MSPE"= min_mspe)
## MSPE 
##   14
MSPE[min_mspe]
## [1] 1.993987

Our MSPE is giving us the MSPE for each number of predictors. The minimum MSPE belongs to our model with 14 variables. Next we want to extract our coefficients “betahats” for our model with 14 variables.

betahat <- coef(search, min_mspe)

week4 <- week4 %>% sample_n(500000)
week4_y <- week4$tip_amount
mf2<-model.frame(tip_amount~.+dow:hours, data=week4)
week4_x<-model.matrix(tip_amount~.+dow:hours, mf2)[,-1]
Xpred = cbind(1, week4_x)[,summary(search)$which[min_mspe,]]
yhat2<- Xpred%*%betahat    
MSPE <- mean((week4_y-yhat2)^2)
c("MSPE week 4" = MSPE)
## MSPE week 4 
##    12.31801
c("sqrt MSPE week 4" = sqrt(MSPE))
## sqrt MSPE week 4 
##         3.509703
c("Variance week 4" = var(week4$tip_amount))
## Variance week 4 
##        6.368398
c("Standard Deviation week4" = sd(week4$tip_amount))
## Standard Deviation week4 
##                 2.523568

The MSPE of our model is 12.31801. MSPE is telling us that based on our predictor variables, approximately how far the ‘true’ tip would be from the thing that is being predicted in our models. Because MSPE is the mean variance of the error, we square-rooted the MSPE to find the standard deviation. This is telling us that there is an error of +-3.509703. Because the value of our standard deviation is low, it is indicating that our prediction is fairly accurate. To be certain our prediction is fairly accurate we need to compare this to the variance and standard deviation of our week 4’s taxi data tip amounts.

Above, when we have calculated our standard deviaiton of our test data’s amount tipped and the square-root of our MSPE, they both appear to have somewhat close values, which validates that our model is fairly good for prediction. What this suggests is that our model shows us some of the variability that is already in the data in which it will provide us with reasonable predicitions for tip amounts based on our given predictor variables.
